# Hard tier tasks — 5 tasks
# Format: task_name|prompt
# Each prompt instructs the agent to work in /tmp/training-TASKNAME/, init a Go module,
# write implementation in main package, include _test.go, and run go test ./... to verify.

concurrent-trie|Work in /tmp/training-trie/. Initialize a Go module (go mod init training/trie). Write trie.go in package main implementing a concurrent trie: type Trie with Insert(word string), Search(word string) bool, Delete(word string) bool — all safe for concurrent use via sync.RWMutex at the node level. Write trie_test.go with unit tests for insert/search/delete correctness and a concurrent test launching 50 goroutines doing interleaved inserts and searches. Also write a BenchmarkInsert in trie_bench_test.go. Run go test -race ./... and go test -bench=. and report. Acceptance: -race clean, benchmark runs.

event-bus|Work in /tmp/training-eventbus/. Initialize a Go module (go mod init training/eventbus). Write bus.go in package main implementing a thread-safe EventBus: Subscribe(topic string, handler func(payload interface{})) (unsub func()), Publish(topic string, payload interface{}), topic wildcards using * suffix (e.g. "user.*" matches "user.created"). Write bus_test.go with tests for exact topic routing, wildcard routing, unsubscribe, and concurrent publish from 10 goroutines. Run go test -race ./... and report. Acceptance: -race clean, wildcard routing correct.

circuit-breaker|Work in /tmp/training-circuitbreaker/. Initialize a Go module (go mod init training/circuitbreaker). Write cb.go in package main implementing: type CircuitBreaker with states closed/open/half-open. NewCircuitBreaker(maxFailures int, resetTimeout time.Duration) *CircuitBreaker. Execute(func() error) error — calls the function when closed or half-open; returns ErrOpen when open. On maxFailures consecutive failures, trips to open; after resetTimeout, moves to half-open. On success in half-open, resets to closed. Write cb_test.go with state-transition tests and a concurrent test. Run go test -race ./... and report. Acceptance: all state transitions tested, -race clean.

bimap|Work in /tmp/training-bimap/. Initialize a Go module (go mod init training/bimap). Write bimap.go in package main implementing a generic bidirectional map: type BiMap[K comparable, V comparable] with Put(k K, v V), GetByKey(k K) (V, bool), GetByValue(v V) (K, bool), DeleteByKey(k K), DeleteByValue(v V), Len() int — all O(1). Write bimap_test.go with table tests for string->int and int->string bimaps, testing overwrite semantics (putting a duplicate key removes the old reverse mapping). Run go test ./... and report. Acceptance: all tests pass, correct overwrite behavior.

sieve-fix|Work in /tmp/training-sieve/. Initialize a Go module (go mod init training/sieve). Write sieve.go in package main with this broken Sieve of Eratosthenes that only works for small N: func Sieve(n int) []int { primes := []int{}; for i := 2; i <= n; i++ { isPrime := true; for j := 2; j < i; j++ { if i%j == 0 { isPrime = false } }; if isPrime { primes = append(primes, i) } }; return primes }. Fix it to use the proper sieve algorithm (boolean array, mark composites) so it runs in O(n log log n) and handles n=10000000 in under 1 second. Write sieve_test.go verifying len(Sieve(10000000))==664579 and a benchmark. Run go test -bench=. ./... and report. Acceptance: correct count, benchmark under 1s.
